result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

ADA Inlow appeared on behalf of the State.  Defendant appeared in person and with Attorney Betthauser.  Defendant plead guilty to count 1 as charged.  Also plead guilty to Count 2 in 14CF115.  All other counts in those 2 cases dismissed and read in, as well as case no. 14CF16.  Court reviewed plea questionnaire, constitutional rights waived and element of the crime.  Priors confirmed.  Voting and firearm warnings given.  Defense stipulated to a factual basis.  Court finds that the defendant freely voluntarily and intelligently entered his plea and waived his constitutional rights.  Find guilty as plead to.  Joint recommendation for 3 years probation, concurrent with any ES/probation now serving.  Court ordered sentence withheld, 3 years probation concurrent.    Not to enter into any bars, taverns, liquor stores, liquor department of grocery stores, the bar areas of restaurants. Defendant may not possess or consume any alcohol, nor be anywhere alcohol is available for consumption on the premises where the defendant is located, except for employment purposes only, and only with his agent's approval.   80 hours CS within 1st 6 months of probation.   Seek and maintain employment.  CC.   The defendant shall comply with any treatment, evaluations and/or programming as deemed appropriate by the COMPAS assessment and the probation agent.  Defendant must sign any releases agent deems necessary to verify defendant's compliance with probation conditions.  Any credit to be determined and stipulated to between the parties.

records.addlTxt: REPORT FOR BOOKING;  Defendant shall not consume any alcohol unless a physician states in writing that the defendant is alcohol dependent and complete withdrawal could endanger the defendant's health or life. In this case a doctor's excuse must be submitted to the Jackson County Clerk of Court or the Jackson County Jail within 48 hours of the bond being signed. Not to enter into any bars, taverns, liquor stores, liquor department of grocery stores, bar areas of restaurants, or where available for consumption on the premises where the defendant is located except for employment purposes only;   As a condition of your release, you must be available 24 hours per day, 7 days a week to submit to testing for alcohol when requested by a law enforcement officer or your probation agent. The defendant may submit to an alcohol test at the Jackson County Sheriff's Office or submit to a PBT by a law enforcement officer. Upon request, the defendant shall appear for and submit to testing within two (2) hours of the official's request.
